Femicides in Italy, an easy solution?

Lately, it seems like everywhere I turn, the buzz is all about femicide and violence against women. The recent tragic murder of Giulia Cecchettin has stirred up quite a storm in Italylike, a really big one.

"I mean, isn't working on well-being and the economy enough to reduce femicides? Duh!"

That was my initial thoughtor, more technically, my hypothesis.

So, I did what's probably the only thing one can do to get closer to the truth; I analyzed the correlation between femicides and well-being.

Findings

Digging into the available data, here's what I've uncovered:

Unfortunately, a population's economic development doesn't guarantee a decrease in femicides.

However, more data is needed to reach a conclusion.

Italy is seriously slacking in the international data game. And that's a big problem.

I scoured the depths, and all I could fish out was a dataset on femicides from 2019.

Can you believe it? Femicide is on everyone's lips, but when it comes to concrete data, Italy seems to be playing hide and seek. Quite a conundrum, don't you think?
